    -Creating our own directive based on Application Requirement called as Custom Directive.

    - In AngularJS we can use Custom Directives in 3 ways.

        1.Element

        2.Attribute

        3.Class

    Ex.

        Custom Directive -- my_directive.

        <my_directive></my_directive>   // Element Level Usage.

        <div my_directive></div>        // Attribute Level Usage.

        <div class="my_directive"></div>    //CSS Class Level Usage.


Properties Of Custom Directives.

1.restrict.

    - it will describe how to use the Custom Directive.

Ex.

app.directive("my_directive",my_directive);

function my_directive(){

    return{
        restrict:"A"
    }
}

<div my_directive></div>


2.template.

    used to add the HTML to the Custom Directive.

Ex.

    app.directive("exampleDirective",exampleDirective);

    function exampleDirective(){
        return{
            restrict:"E",
            template:"<b>This is Custom Directive</b>"
        }
    }

    Ex.

        <example-directive></example-directive>

3.templateUrl.

    used to add the external template to the custom directive.

Ex.

--------------------
templates
    sample.html
--------------------
<b>This is Custom Directive</b>

app.directive("exampleDirective",exampleDirective);
function exampleDirective(){
    return{
        restrict:"A",
        templateUrl:"templates/sample.html"
    }
}

<div example-directive></div>

4.controller.

    - used to define the controller for template of a Custom Directive.

---------------
templates
    sample.html
---------------

sample.html

{{var_one}}

--------------
controllers
    ctrl.js
--------------

app.controller("ctrl",ctrl);
ctrl.$inject=["$scope"];
function ctrl($scope){
    $scope.var_one="I am from Custom Directive";
}

-----------------
directives
    exampleDirective.js
-----------------
app.directive("exampleDirective",exampleDirective);
function exampleDirective(){
    return{
        restrict:"C",
        templateUrl:"templates/sample.html",
        controller:"ctrl"
    }
}

----------------------
<div class="example-directive"></div>







